article.headline: Wizards get rare back-to-back wins
article.linkText: Wizards come from 18 back against Bulls
article.story:
WASHINGTON (AP) -- The Washington Wizards haven't overcome many large deficits this season. They haven't won consecutive games very often, either. On Monday, they did both. The Wizards overcame an 18-point first-half deficit to beat the Chicago Bulls 93-83, recording their first two-game winning streak in two months. Washington was held scoreless for nearly five minutes in the fourth quarter but held the Bulls to 25 points in the second half. Since beating Atlanta on Nov. 17 and Cleveland two days later, Washington had gone 5-22 before Saturday's 99-84 win over Seattle. Playing without Jerry Stackhouse for the entire season and Gilbert Arenas for much of it, the Wizards also were without Brevin Knight, who injured a knuckle on his shooting hand Saturday. Washington coach Eddie Jordan started rookie Steve Blake at point guard, playing him for 45 minutes -- 11 more than in any game this season. Blake and Juan Dixon shut down Jamal Crawford and Kirk Hinrich in the second half. In less than two minutes in the second quarter, Hinrich scored 10 straight points for Chicago. In the second half, he missed all four of his field-goal attempts. "We went small, and our smalls really get after it on the perimeter," Jordan said. The Bulls led 58-40 with 1:13 to play in the first half, and led 58-43 at the break. "This is a tough one to swallow. Of all of our losses, this is probably the worst one," Crawford said. "It wasn't like we were up 18 on the Kings or the Lakers or somebody. It was the Wizards." When the teams met last on Dec. 27, Crawford had a career-high 42. On Monday, he had 19, just five in the second half. "That was just embarrassing. The rim seemed like it had a lid on it in the second half," he said. Even though the Wizards trailed at halftime, they believed they could come back. "We decided to play some great team defense. That's what we did at halftime," Blake said. "We went out there and did it." Dixon's jumper with 3:21 to play gave the Wizards an 83-81 lead, and a minute later he stole the ball from Hinrich and scored on a layup. He had 17 points and five steals. Chicago, which is on its fourth losing streak of at least four games, held the Wizards scoreless for nearly five minutes in the fourth quarter and led 81-75 with 4:56 to play. But the Bulls were outscored 18-2 over the rest of the game. "Myself and the rest of the team just stopped being aggressive," Hinrich said. "We can't do that at all. They picked up their intensity and their aggressiveness and we just couldn't match it." Larry Hughes, who had 25 points to lead the Wizards, passed the 5,000-point mark with his second field goal of the game.

Game notes
Christian Laettner sat out the final game of a five-game suspension for violating the NBA's substance abuse policy. ... For the second consecutive game, Jarvis Hayes set a career high with rebounds. He had 13 on Saturday against Seattle and 14 against Chicago. ... Chicago's Tyson Chandler, who has been on the injured list since Dec. 1 with lower back pain, is traveling with the team for the first time since then.
